Fall notes that climate shocks in the region have become too frequent, even though the nations paying the price contribute the least to the global climate crisis. The UNICEF Regional Director is currently in Malawi, assessing response efforts of UNICEF teams on the ground following storm Anna which affected approximately 15 000 people in Nsanje and Chikwawa districts in the Southern part of the country. “We all know how Malawi is prone to these kinds of shocks which are becoming frequent. “The shock frequency that we are witnessing mainly in this part of the world clearly indicates that the climate crisis is one of the biggest threats humanity is facing”, said Fall. He elaborates further on the plight of African countries facing this crisis…  (click on the link below)